# Network Automation: Router Configuration & Backup using Python

## Project Goal
   1. Initial Router Configuration
   2. Backup of running configs

## Tools Required
   1. Python
   2. GNS3 or Cisco Packet Tracer 
   3. Netmiko

## Network Topology (Simple but Effective)
    2 Routers (R1, R2)
    1 Switch
    Your PC (automation machine)

## FOLLOW THE SEQUENCE
 Step 1: Configure Router for SSH (Manual One-Time Setup)
         On each router:
 Bash:   hostname R1
         ip domain-name lab.local
         crypto key generate rsa
         username admin password cisco
         line vty 0 4
         login local
         transport input ssh

         Assign IP to interface:
Bash:    interface g0/0
         ip address 192.168.1.1 255.255.255.0
         no shutdown

Step 2: Python Script – Send Config Automatically
Python:
from netmiko import ConnectHandler

router = {
    "device_type": "cisco_ios",
    "host": "192.168.1.1",
    "username": "admin",
    "password": "cisco",
}

commands = [
    "interface g0/1",
    "ip address 10.10.10.1 255.255.255.0",
    "no shutdown",
    "router ospf 1",
    "network 10.10.10.0 0.0.0.255 area 0"
]

connection = ConnectHandler(**router)

output = connection.send_config_set(commands)

print(output)

connection.disconnect() 

Step 3: Backup Configuration Script
Python:
from netmiko import ConnectHandler

router = {
    "device_type": "cisco_ios",
    "host": "192.168.1.1",
    "username": "admin",
    "password": "cisco",
}

connection = ConnectHandler(**router)

output = connection.send_command("show running-config")

with open("R1_backup.txt", "w") as file:
    file.write(output)

connection.disconnect()

print("Backup completed!")

